{
  "texts": [
    "Consequently, our approach may help overcome any self-selection bias present in loneliness intervention studies given the stigma that might prevent individuals from seeking help (Lau & Gruen, 1992).",
    "Not only does it afford support for those who are experiencing loneliness (without requiring them to seek out interventions), but also it helps facilitates an organizational culture high in social connection that benefits all employees (Holt-Lunstad, 2022).",
    "Our study also provides tentative evidence that supervisor support interventions may be particularly beneficial for those who report higher initial levels of loneliness.",
    "Specifically, among those higher in loneliness at baseline, exposure to the intervention reduced loneliness, and increased perceptions of emotional support and destigmatizing behaviors from supervisors.",
    "This finding is consistent with theory that social support provision may be most beneficial to those who are experiencing low social connection from their coworkers or work group (military unit in this study), in line with the negativity buffer role of social support (Bavik et al., 2020)."
  ]
}